, now in coll. 
<emphasis id="B900EABD206DFFBDFB0B8746FABF4CFC" bold="true" box="[1193,1282,1647,1673]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">MNHU</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCB36AF206DFFBDFF6587BAFD0A4D14" blockId="7.[151,1437,1502,2034]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis id="B900EABD206DFFBDFF6587BAFEE44CD8" bold="true" box="[199,345,1683,1709]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Description.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="134F2A2A206DFFBDFEC487BAFE6A4CD8" box="[358,471,1683,1709]" captionStart="FIGURES 3–15" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1785,1809]" captionTargetBox="[181,1408,201,1744]" captionTargetId="figure-28@6.[177,1411,181,1761]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 3–15. Wing pattern. Figs 3–8: Hydria cervinalis cervinalis: Fig. 3, ♂, Germany, Sachsen-Anhalt, Mansfeld; Fig. 4, ♂, Ungarn, prov. Vesprérn, Zsofiapuszta; Fig. 5, ♂, Germany, Ug. Freyburg Zscheiplitz, Schafberg; Fig. 6, ♂, Germany, Umg. Jena; Figs 7 and 8, ♂, Germany, Sachsen-Anhalt, Mansfeld; Figs 9–10: H. cervinalis taurica ssp. n., Turkey, prov. Antalya, Civizli W Seydisehir, Fig. 9, Holotype ♂, (g. prep. DS-120/2012); Fig. 10, Paratype ♀, (g. prep. DS-121/2012); Figs 11–12: H. gernoti sp. n., Turkey, prov. Nigde, Ala Dagi: Fig. 11, Holotype ♂; Fig. 12, Paratype ♀; Figs 13–15: H. schachti sp. n.: Fig. 13, Holotype ♂, Turkey, prov. Erzurum, Meschit Daglari; Fig. 14, Paratype ♀, Turkey, prov. Erzurum, Meschit Daglari; Fig. 15, Paratype ♂, Turkey, prov. Erzurum, Karadeniz Daglari, Korga Dari. a = upperside; b = underside." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896501/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Figs 9–10</figureCitation>
) Large subspecies with a wingspan in males 
<quantity id="4C8C9B4A206DFFBDFC6487BAFBFD4CDB" box="[966,1088,1683,1710]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" metricValueMax="3.9" metricValueMin="3.7" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" unit="mm" value="38.0" valueMax="39.0" valueMin="37.0">37–39 mm</quantity>
, in females 
<quantity id="4C8C9B4A206DFFBDFB6187BAFA804CDB" box="[1219,1341,1683,1710]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.85" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.7" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" unit="mm" value="38.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="37.0">37–40 mm</quantity>
. Ground colour of forewing on average somewhat lighter than in typical 
<taxonomicName id="4C744D2C206DFFBDFCC3879EFB274CA4" authority="cervinalis" box="[865,1178,1719,1745]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="cervinalis" subSpecies="cervinalis">
<emphasis id="B900EABD206DFFBDFCC3879EFB274CA4" box="[865,1178,1719,1745]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Hydria cervinalis cervinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Basal half of terminal area lightened, ochre-brown, well contrasting with the postmedian. Transverse lines faint or absent. Underside of the wings dull grey-brown. Discal spots and postmedian fascia distinct, dark grey. The postmedian running more or less straight towards costa. At vein R5 somewhat curved basally up to the costa, reaching the latter in an acute or right angle. Transverse lines indistinct or absent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCB36AF206DFFBDFF658642FC9A4DF0" blockId="7.[151,1437,1502,2034]" box="[199,807,1899,1926]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis id="B900EABD206DFFBDFF658642FDBE4DF0" bold="true" box="[199,515,1899,1925]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Male and female genitalia.</emphasis>
See Diagnose part below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36E6524206DFFB2FF6586A6FCD84BFC" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="509" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCB36AF206DFFB2FF6586A6FBD24B34" blockId="7.[151,1437,1502,2034]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="509" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">
<emphasis id="B900EABD206DFFBDFF6586A6FEFF4DDC" bold="true" box="[199,322,1935,1961]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C744D2C206DFFBDFEEB86A6FDDB4DDC" authority="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei, 2022" authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" box="[329,614,1935,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="cervinalis" status="ssp. n." subSpecies="taurica">
<emphasis id="B900EABD206DFFBDFEEB86A6FDDB4DDC" box="[329,614,1935,1961]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Hydria cervinalis taurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23357C6206DFFBDFDCF86B9FD094DDF" box="[621,692,1936,1962]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" rank="subSpecies">ssp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is very similar to the nominate subspecies in external appearance. However, on forewing upper side the terminal area is remarkably lightened towards postmedian fascia and transverse lines are more or less absent. On wing underside in the new subspecies the transverse lines, except the postmedian fascia, are nearly absent. The latter is running usually straighter than in the nominate subspecies. Male genitalia are very similar to the nominate subspecies, with shorter apical part of uncus and broader valva in 
<taxonomicName id="4C744D2C2062FFB2FB518192FACB4AA1" authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" box="[1267,1398,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="cervinalis" subSpecies="taurica">
ssp. 
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FA878192FACB4AA1" box="[1317,1398,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">taurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In addition, in the new subspecies juxta is less elongated, its median fork is more prominent (see 
<figureCitation id="134F2A2A2062FFB2FB0681F6FA9D4A8C" box="[1188,1312,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–30" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1858,1882]" captionTargetBox="[215,1377,190,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-20@17.[207,1380,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 26–30. Male genitalia. Fig. 26: Hydria cervinalis cervinalis (Germany, Kaiserstuhl, Badberg, g. prep. 2326/2020 H. Rajaei); Fig. 27: Hydria cervinalis taurica subsp. n., Paratype, (Turkey, prov. Antalya, Civizli W Seydisehir, g. prep. DS- 122/2012); Fig. 28: Hydria gernoti sp. n., Paratype, (Turkey, Nigde, Ala Dagi, g. prep. DS 99/2012); Fig. 29: Hydria schachti sp. n. Paratype (Turkey, Ispir, g. prep. DS-112/2012); Fig. 30, Hydria (cf.) sp. n., paratype (Azerbaijan, Talysh, Zuvand, g. prep. DS-05/2012); a = genitalia capsule; b = aedeagus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896509/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Figs 26, 27</figureCitation>
) compared to the nominate subspecies. Female genitalia of new subspecies are similar to that of nominate subspecies, but the ductus bursae is narrower and slightly longer than in nominate subspecies (
<figureCitation id="134F2A2A2062FFB2FC42800EFBDF4B34" box="[992,1122,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–47" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1791,1815]" captionTargetBox="[237,1345,194,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-28@20.[229,1359,181,1768]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 40–47. Female genitalia. Fig. 40: Hydria cervinalis cervinalis (Germany, Kaiserstuhl, Badberg, g. prep. 2327/2020 H. Rajaei); Fig. 41: Hydria cervinalis taurica subsp. n., Paratype, (Turkey, prov. Antalya, Civizli W Seydisehir, g. prep. DS- 121/2012); Fig. 42: Hydria gernoti sp. n., Paratype, (Turkey, prov. Nigde, Ala Dagi, g. prep. 2317/2020 H. Rajaei); Fig. 43: Hydria schachti sp. n. Paratype (Georgia, Achaltzych, g. prep. LL 38/2011); Fig. 44. Hydria gaudarica (Spain, Albarracin, g. prep. DS-107/2012); Fig. 45: Hydria hyrcana, syntype (Iran, Hajiabad, g. prep. 1555 H. Rajaei); Fig. 46: Hydria montivagata montivagata (Switzerland, Zermatt, g. prep. 2329/2020 H. Rajaei); Fig. 47, Hydria loebeli sp. n., Patatype (Turkey, prov. Nigde, Aladag, g. prep. DS-175/2012)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896515" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896515/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Figs 40, 41</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCB36AF2062FFB2FF658063FCD84BFC" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FF658063FE884B11" bold="true" box="[199,309,330,356]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Genetics.</emphasis>
The single sequenced barcode of the new subspecies (GWOTL494-13) is clustered with 
<taxonomicName id="4C744D2C2062FFB2FAAF8062FA214B10" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1763" box="[1293,1436,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cervinalis">
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FAAF8062FA214B10" box="[1293,1436,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">H. cervinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F363763F2062FFB2FF778046FE804BFC" box="[213,317,367,393]" name="Germany" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Germany</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F363763F2062FFB2FED18046FE1B4BFC" box="[371,422,367,393]" name="Italy" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Italy</collectingCountry>
with 2.63% minimum genetic distance.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36E65242062FFB2FF6580BBFB8F484B" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BCB36AF2062FFB2FF6580BBFCD84BD8" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" box="[199,869,402,429]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FF6580BBFEDC4BD9" bold="true" box="[199,353,402,428]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus id="54CF880D2062FFB2FDC280BAFD2D4BD8" box="[608,656,403,429]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingCountry id="F363763F2062FFB2FCAD80BAFCDC4BD8" box="[783,865,403,429]" name="Turkey" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Turkey</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCB36AF2062FFB2FF65809FFDA8486C" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FF65809FFE974BA5" bold="true" box="[199,298,438,464]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Habitat.</emphasis>
The new subspecies inhabits sub-continental summer-green open deciduous forests dominated by 
<taxonomicName id="4C744D2C2062FFB2FF3580F2FEFD4B81" box="[151,320,475,501]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cerris">
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FF3580F2FEFD4B81" box="[151,320,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Quercus cerris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., open forest and rocky slopes at the continental escarpments of the Middle Taurus Mountains between 
<quantity id="4C8C9B4A2062FFB2FF5980D6FE19486C" box="[251,420,511,537]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" unit="m" value="1350.0" valueMax="1700.0" valueMin="1000.0">
<geoCoordinate id="EE4050682062FFB2FF5980D6FE87486C" box="[251,314,511,537]" degrees="1,000" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" precision="55" value="1.0">1,000</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="EE4050682062FFB2FE9880D6FE35486C" box="[314,392,511,537]" degrees="1,700" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" precision="55" value="-1.7">–1,700</geoCoordinate>
m
</quantity>
(
<figureCitation id="134F2A2A2062FFB2FE1680D6FDB5486C" box="[436,520,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 71–77" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1728,1752]" captionTargetBox="[249,1339,183,1703]" captionTargetId="figure-20@23.[249,1339,181,1704]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 71–77. Photos of habitat and adult specimens. Fig. 71. Col Du Zad, province Khenifra, Morocco. The locality is a habitat of Hydria gudarica (DUFaY, 1983) at 2,135m. The habitat is an open Cedar forest mixed with dry, species-rich meadows (photo. noRbERT PöLL); Fig. 72. Turkey, Middle Taurus, Civizli, type locality of Hydria cervinalis taurica ssp. n. during the flight period of the adults in mid-May. The forests in the background are dominated by Quercus cerris and Juniperus excelsa. At forest clearings Berberis species and wild Pyrus trees are present (photo DIRK STaDIE); Fig. 73. Hydria gernoti sp.n. male PT, Turkey, Province Nigde, Als dagi, Sulucaova vic., 2,100m, ex ovo (photo DIRK STaDIE); Figs 74–75. Type locality of Hydria gernoti sp. n. in the Ala dagi mountains at 2,300m in mid-May. In foreground right some leafless bushes of Berberis (photo DIRK STaDIE, RaLF FIEbIG); Figs 76–77. Habitat of Hydria loebeli sp. n. and H. gernoti sp. n., small river valley near Göreme, Central Turkey (photo DIRK STaDIE, RaLF FIEbIG)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5896521" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5896521/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCB36AF2062FFB2FF65830AFB8F484B" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" box="[199,1074,547,574]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FF65830AFEF44848" bold="true" box="[199,329,547,573]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Phenology.</emphasis>
Adults of 
<taxonomicName id="4C744D2C2062FFB2FE1D830AFDFC4849" authorityName="Stadie &amp; Fiebig &amp; Rajaei" authorityYear="2022" box="[447,577,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Hydria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="cervinalis" subSpecies="taurica">
ssp. 
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FE52830AFDFC4849" box="[496,577,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">taurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
wereobserved mid-May (very limited data).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36E65242062FFB2FF65836FFE3248F3" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BCB36AF2062FFB2FF65836FFE3248F3" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FF65836FFE9A4815" bold="true" box="[199,295,582,608]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Biology.</emphasis>
Most probably the larvae of the new subspecies feed also on one of the Turkish 
<taxonomicName id="4C744D2C2062FFB2FB3E836EFAEE4814" box="[1180,1363,583,609]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Berberidaceae" genus="Berberis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FB3E836EFB414814" box="[1180,1276,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Berberis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
(more investigation needed).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36E65242062FFB2FF6583A6FCFC48B8" pageId="8" pageNumber="509" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BCB36AF2062FFB2FF6583A6FCFC48B8" blockId="8.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis id="B900EABD2062FFB2FF6583A6FE8648DC" bold="true" box="[199,315,655,681]" pageId="8" pageNumber="509">Remarks.</emphasis>
It is to expect that the taxon merits species rank by zoogeographic reasons. The material is very scarce. Further investigation is needed to solve this question.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
